[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In thermodynamics, the principle of **detailed balance** says that every process of energy transfer in one direction must also allow energy transfer in the opposite direction, and in equilibrium, the flux in both directions must be equal.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For example, the principle can be used in kinetic systems which are decomposed into elementary processes (collisions, or steps, or elementary reactions).
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] It states that at equilibrium, each elementary process is in equilibrium with its reverse process.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance was explicitly introduced for collisions by Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In 1872, he proved his H-theorem using this principle.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The arguments in favor of this property are founded upon microscopic reversibility.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Five years before Boltzmann, James Clerk Maxwell used the principle of detailed balance for gas kinetics with the reference to the principle of sufficient reason.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] He compared the idea of detailed balance with other types of balancing (like cyclic balance) and found that "Now it is impossible to assign a reason" why detailed balance should be rejected (p.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In 1901, Rudolf Wegscheider introduced the principle of detailed balance for chemical kinetics.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In particular, he demonstrated that the irreversible cycles ${\ce {A1->A2->\cdots ->A_{\mathit {n}}->A1}}$ are impossible and found explicitly the relations between kinetic constants that follow from the principle of detailed balance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In 1931, Lars Onsager used these relations in his works, for which he was awarded the 1968 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance has been used in Markov chain Monte Carlo methods since their invention in 1953.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In particular, in the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and in its important particular case, Gibbs sampling, it is used as a simple and reliable condition to provide the desirable equilibrium state.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Now, the principle of detailed balance is a standard part of the university courses in statistical mechanics, physical chemistry, chemical and physical kinetics.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The microscopic "reversing of time" turns at the kinetic level into the "reversing of arrows": the elementary processes transform into their reverse processes.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The equilibrium ensemble should be invariant with respect to this transformation because of microreversibility and the uniqueness of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] This leads us immediately to the concept of detailed balance: each process is equilibrated by its reverse process.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The macroscopic elementary processes are microscopically distinguishable.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] That is, they represent disjoint sets of microscopic events.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Any of these assumptions may be violated.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For example, Boltzmann's collision can be represented as ${\ce {A_{\mathit {v}}+A_{\mathit {w}}->A_{\mathit {v'}}+A_{\mathit {w'}}}}$ , where ${\ce {A}}_{v}$ is a particle with velocity *v*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Therefore, the collision is transformed into the reverse collision by the *PT* transformation, where *P* is the space inversion and *T* is the time reversal.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Detailed balance for Boltzmann's equation requires *PT*-invariance of collisions' dynamics, not just *T*-invariance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For this purpose, we need to apply additionally the space reversal *P*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Therefore, for the detailed balance in Boltzmann's equation not *T*-invariance but *PT*-invariance is needed.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Equilibrium may be not *T*- or *PT*-invariant even if the laws of motion are invariant.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] This non-invariance may be caused by the spontaneous symmetry breaking.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] There exist *nonreciprocal media* (for example, some bi-isotropic materials) without *T* and *PT* invariance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] If different macroscopic processes are sampled from the same elementary microscopic events then macroscopic detailed balance may be violated even when microscopic detailed balance holds.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Now, after almost 150 years of development, the scope of validity and the violations of detailed balance in kinetics seem to be clear.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] *P**ij* = *P*(*X**t* = *j* | *X**t* − 1 = *i*), and π*i* and π*j* are the equilibrium probabilities of being in states *i* and *j*, respectively.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] When Pr(*X**t*−1 = *i*) = π*i* for all *i*, this is equivalent to the joint probability matrix, Pr(*X**t*−1 = *i*, *X**t* = *j*) being symmetric in *i* and *j*; or symmetric in *t* − 1 and *t*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Transition matrices that are symmetric (*P**ij* = *P**ji* or *P*(*s*′, *s*) = *P*(*s*, *s*′)) always have detailed balance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In these cases, a uniform distribution over the states is an equilibrium distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Reversibility is equivalent to Kolmogorov's criterion: the product of transition rates over any closed loop of states is the same in both directions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For example, it implies that, for all *a*, *b* and *c*, $P(a,b)P(b,c)P(c,a)=P(a,c)P(c,b)P(b,a)\,.$ For example, if we have a Markov chain with three states such that only these transitions are possible: $A\to B,B\to C,C\to A,B\to A$ , then they violate Kolmogorov's criterion.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For continuous systems with detailed balance, it may be possible to continuously transform the coordinates until the equilibrium distribution is uniform, with a transition kernel which then is symmetric.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In the case of discrete states, it may be possible to achieve something similar by breaking the Markov states into appropriately-sized degenerate sub-states.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For a Markov transition matrix and a stationary distribution, the detailed balance equations may not be valid.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] However, it can be shown that a unique Markov transition matrix exists which is closest according to the stationary distribution and a given norm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The closest Matrix can be computed by solving a quadratic-convex optimization problem.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For many systems of physical and chemical kinetics, detailed balance provides *sufficient conditions* for the strict increase of entropy in isolated systems.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For example, the famous Boltzmann H-theorem states that, according to the Boltzmann equation, the principle of detailed balance implies positivity of entropy production.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The Boltzmann formula (1872) for entropy production in rarefied gas kinetics with detailed balance served as a prototype of many similar formulas for dissipation in mass action kinetics and generalized mass action kinetics with detailed balance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Nevertheless, the principle of detailed balance is not necessary for entropy growth.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For example, in the linear irreversible cycle ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 -> A1}}$ , entropy production is positive but the principle of detailed balance does not hold.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Thus, the principle of detailed balance is a sufficient but not necessary condition for entropy increase in Boltzmann kinetics.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] These relations between the principle of detailed balance and the second law of thermodynamics were clarified in 1887 when Hendrik Lorentz objected to the Boltzmann H-theorem for polyatomic gases.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Lorentz stated that the principle of detailed balance is not applicable to collisions of polyatomic molecules.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Boltzmann immediately invented a new, more general condition sufficient for entropy growth.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Boltzmann's condition holds for all Markov processes, irrespective of time-reversibility.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Later, entropy increase was proved for all Markov processes by a direct method.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] These theorems may be considered as simplifications of the Boltzmann result.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Later, this condition was referred to as the "cyclic balance" condition (because it holds for irreversible cycles) or the "semi-detailed balance" or the "complex balance".
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In 1981, Carlo Cercignani and Maria Lampis proved that the Lorentz arguments were wrong and the principle of detailed balance is valid for polyatomic molecules.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Nevertheless, the extended semi-detailed balance conditions invented by Boltzmann in this discussion remain the remarkable generalization of the detailed balance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Here, the reverse reactions with positive constants are included in the list separately.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] We need this separation of direct and reverse reactions to apply later the general formalism to the systems with some irreversible reactions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The system of stoichiometric equations of elementary reactions is the *reaction mechanism*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The *stoichiometric vector* $\gamma _{r}$ is the *r*th row of ${\boldsymbol {\Gamma }}$ with coordinates $\gamma _{ri}=\beta _{ri}-\alpha _{ri}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] According to the *generalized mass action law*, the reaction rate for an elementary reaction is $w_{r}=k_{r}\prod _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}^{\alpha _{ri}}\,,$ where $a_{i}\geq 0$ is the activity (the "effective concentration") of $A_{i}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The reaction mechanism includes reactions with the reaction rate constants $k_{r}>0$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For a reversible reaction, $K_{r}=k_{r}^{+}/k_{r}^{-}$ is the equilibrium constant.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance for the generalized mass action law is: For given values $k_{r}$ there exists a positive equilibrium $a_{i}^{\rm {eq}}>0$ that satisfies detailed balance, that is, $w_{r}^{+}=w_{r}^{-}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The following classical result gives the necessary and sufficient conditions for the existence of a positive equilibrium $a_{i}^{\rm {eq}}>0$ with detailed balance (see, for example, the textbook).
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In particular, for any cycle in the monomolecular (linear) reactions the product of the reaction rate constants in the clockwise direction is equal to the product of the reaction rate constants in the counterclockwise direction.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The same condition is valid for the reversible Markov processes (it is equivalent to the "no net flow" condition).
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The computational aspect of the Wegscheider conditions was studied by D.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The Wegscheider conditions demonstrate that whereas the principle of detailed balance states a local property of equilibrium, it implies the relations between the kinetic constants that are valid for all states far from equilibrium.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] This is possible because a kinetic law is known and relations between the rates of the elementary processes at equilibrium can be transformed into relations between kinetic constants which are used globally.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For the Wegscheider conditions this kinetic law is the law of mass action (or the generalized law of mass action).
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] To describe dynamics of the systems that obey the generalized mass action law, one has to represent the activities as functions of the concentrations *cj* and temperature.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The chemical potential can be represented as a function of *c* and *T*, where *c* is the vector of concentrations with components *cj*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For the ideal systems, $\mu _{i}=RT\ln c_{i}+\mu _{i}^{\ominus }$ and $a_{j}=c_{j}$ : the activity is the concentration and the generalized mass action law is the usual law of mass action.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Consider a system in isothermal (*T*=const) isochoric (the volume *V*=const) condition.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For these conditions, the Helmholtz free energy ⁠ $F(T,V,N)$ ⁠ measures the "useful" work obtainable from a system.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] It is a functions of the temperature *T*, the volume *V* and the amounts of chemical components *Nj* (usually measured in moles), *N* is the vector with components *Nj*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The chemical potential is a partial derivative: $\mu _{i}=\partial F(T,V,N)/\partial N_{i}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Let the principle of detailed balance be valid.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] These symmetry relations, $L_{ij}=L_{ji}$ , are exactly the Onsager reciprocal relations.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The coefficient matrix L is non-positive.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] It is negative on the linear span of the stoichiometric vectors $\gamma _{r}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] So, the Onsager relations follow from the principle of detailed balance in the linear approximation near equilibrium.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] There need not be a (global) detailed balance as reservoirs can have different temperatures, chemical potentials, etc.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In mathematical terms, the condition of local detailed balance assures that the logarithmic ratio of the probability of a trajectory to the probability of the time-reversed trajectory equals the entropy flux per *k*B to the system environment.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] It is important here that the environment consists of mutually separated thermodynamic equilibrium baths.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] In particular, local detailed balance allows identification of currents and entropy flows, and is directly related to the so-called fluctuation theorems for entropy fluxes.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] As shown in a series of publications, local detailed balance implies detailed, integrated, local, steady-state or transient fluctuation theorems for the entropy flux satisfying a Gallavotti–Cohen-like symmetry.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Discussions and derivations of local detailed balance are found in.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Not all models that are commonly used in nonequilibrium statistical mechanics satisfy local detailed balance, which makes it less evident how to associate heat and entropy fluxes to the proposed dynamics.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] To formulate the principle of semi-detailed balance, it is convenient to count the direct and inverse elementary reactions separately.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Let Y be the set of all these vectors $\alpha _{r},\beta _{r}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] $r\in R_{\nu }^{+}$ if and only if $\nu$ is the vector of the input stoichiometric coefficients $\alpha _{r}$ for the *r*th elementary reaction; $r\in R_{\nu }^{-}$ if and only if $\nu$ is the vector of the output stoichiometric coefficients $\beta _{r}$ for the *r*th elementary reaction.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For the Markov kinetics the semi-detailed balance condition is just the elementary balance equation and holds for any steady state.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For the nonlinear mass action law it is, in general, sufficient but not necessary condition for stationarity.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The semi-detailed balance condition is weaker than the detailed balance one: if the principle of detailed balance holds then the condition of semi-detailed balance also holds.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Boltzmann introduced the semi-detailed balance condition for collisions in 1887 and proved that it guaranties the positivity of the entropy production.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For chemical kinetics, this condition (as the *complex balance* condition) was introduced by Horn and Jackson in 1972.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The microscopic backgrounds for the semi-detailed balance were found in the Markov microkinetics of the intermediate compounds that are present in small amounts and whose concentrations are in quasiequilibrium with the main components.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Under these microscopic assumptions, the semi-detailed balance condition is just the balance equation for the Markov microkinetics according to the **Michaelis–Menten–Stueckelberg theorem**.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The exponential term is called the *Boltzmann factor* and the multiplier $\varphi _{r}\geq 0$ is the kinetic factor.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For $\lambda =1$ it is just the sum of the reaction rates.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The function $\theta (\lambda )$ is convex because $\theta ''(\lambda )\geq 0$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Direct calculation gives that according to the kinetic equations ${\frac {dF}{dt}}=-VRT\left.{\frac {d\theta (\lambda )}{d\lambda }}\right|_{\lambda =1}$ This is *the general dissipation formula for the generalized mass action law*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The semi-detailed balance condition can be transformed into identity $\theta (0)\equiv \theta (1)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Therefore, for the systems with semi-detailed balance ${dF}/{dt}\leq 0$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] The **cone theorem** states that for the given reaction mechanism and given positive equilibrium, the velocity (*dN/dt*) at a state *N* for a system with complex balance belongs to the cone $\mathbf {Q} _{\rm {DB}}(N)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] That is, there exists a system with detailed balance, the same reaction mechanism, the same positive equilibrium, that gives the same velocity at state *N*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] According to cone theorem, for a given state *N*, the set of velocities of the semidetailed balance systems coincides with the set of velocities of the detailed balance systems if their reaction mechanisms and equilibria coincide.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] Detailed balance states that in equilibrium each elementary process is equilibrated by its reverse process and requires reversibility of all elementary processes.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For many real physico-chemical complex systems (e.g. homogeneous combustion, heterogeneous catalytic oxidation, most enzyme reactions etc.), detailed mechanisms include both reversible and irreversible reactions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] If one represents irreversible reactions as limits of reversible steps, then it becomes obvious that not all reaction mechanisms with irreversible reactions can be obtained as limits of systems or reversible reactions with detailed balance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/detailed-balance] For example, the irreversible cycle ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 -> A1}}$ cannot be obtained as such a limit but the reaction mechanism ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 <- A1}}$ can.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Let $X\colon \Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ be a random variable in some probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},\mathbb {P} )$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] We wish to estimate the expected value of X under $\mathbb {P}$ , denoted $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] The basic idea of importance sampling is to sample from a different distribution to lower the variance of the estimation of $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ , or when sampling directly from $\mathbb {P}$ is difficult.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] This is accomplished by first choosing a random variable $Y\geq 0$ such that $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[Y]=1$ and that $\mathbb {P}$ -almost everywhere $Y(\omega )\neq 0$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] When X is of constant sign over $\Omega$ , the best variable Y would clearly be $Y^{*}={\frac {X}{\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]}}\geq 0$ , so that $X/Y^{*}$ is the searched constant $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ and a single sample under $\mathbb {Q} ^{*}$ suffices to give its value.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Unfortunately we cannot take that choice, because $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ is precisely the value we are looking for!
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] therefore, a good probability change $\mathbb {Q}$ in importance sampling will redistribute the law of X so that its samples' frequencies are sorted directly according to their contributions in $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ as opposed to $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[1]$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Importance sampling is often used as a Monte Carlo integrator.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] When $\mathbb {P}$ is the uniform distribution over $\Omega =\mathbb {R}$ , the expectation $\mathbb {E} _{\mathbb {P} }[X]$ corresponds to the integral of the real function $X\colon \mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Such methods are frequently used to estimate posterior densities or expectations in state and/or parameter estimation problems in probabilistic models that are too hard to treat analytically.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Examples include Bayesian networks and importance weighted variational autoencoders.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] The fundamental issue in implementing importance sampling simulation is the choice of the biased distribution which encourages the important regions of the input variables.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Choosing or designing a good biased distribution is the "art" of importance sampling.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] The rewards for a good distribution can be huge run-time savings; the penalty for a bad distribution can be longer run times than for a general Monte Carlo simulation without importance sampling.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Consider X to be the sample and ${\frac {f(X)}{g(X)}}$ to be the likelihood ratio, where f is the probability density (mass) function of the desired distribution and g is the probability density (mass) function of the biased/proposal/sample distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Notice that when $X\geq 0$ , this variance becomes 0.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Consider estimating by simulation the probability $p_{t}\,$ of an event $X\geq t$ , where X is a random variable with cumulative distribution function $F(x)$ and probability density function $f(x)=F'(x)\,$ , where prime denotes derivative.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] A K -length independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) sequence $X_{i}\,$ is generated from the distribution F , and the number $k_{t}$ of random variables that lie above the threshold t are counted.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Note that the variance is low if $p_{t}\approx 1$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Importance sampling is concerned with the determination and use of an alternate density function $f_{*}\,$ (for X ), usually referred to as a biasing density, for the simulation experiment.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] This density allows the event ${X\geq t\ }$ to occur more frequently, so the sequence lengths K gets smaller for a given estimator variance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Alternatively, for a given K , use of the biasing density results in a variance smaller than that of the conventional Monte Carlo estimate.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] From the definition of $p_{t}\,$ , we can introduce $f_{*}\,$ as below.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] is a likelihood ratio and is referred to as the weighting function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] This is the importance sampling estimator of $p_{t}\,$ and is unbiased.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] That is, the estimation procedure is to generate i.i.d. samples from $f_{*}\,$ and for each sample which exceeds $t\,$ , the estimate is incremented by the weight $W\,$ evaluated at the sample value.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] The results are averaged over $K\,$ trials.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Now, the importance sampling problem then focuses on finding a biasing density $f_{*}\,$ such that the variance of the importance sampling estimator is less than the variance of the general Monte Carlo estimate.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] For some biasing density function, which minimizes the variance, and under certain conditions reduces it to zero, it is called an optimal biasing density function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Although there are many kinds of biasing methods, the following two methods are most widely used in the applications of importance sampling.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Shifting probability mass into the event region ${X\geq t\ }$ by positive scaling of the random variable $X\,$ with a number greater than unity has the effect of increasing the variance (mean also) of the density function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] This results in a heavier tail of the density, leading to an increase in the event probability.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Scaling is probably one of the earliest biasing methods known and has been extensively used in practice.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] It is simple to implement and usually provides conservative simulation gains as compared to other methods.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] In importance sampling by scaling, the simulation density is chosen as the density function of the scaled random variable $aX\,$ , where usually $a>1$ for tail probability estimation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] While scaling shifts probability mass into the desired event region, it also pushes mass into the complementary region $X<t\,$ which is undesirable.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] If $X\,$ is a sum of $n\,$ random variables, the spreading of mass takes place in an $n\,$ dimensional space.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] The consequence of this is a decreasing importance sampling gain for increasing $n\,$ , and is called the dimensionality effect.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] A modern version of importance sampling by scaling is e.g. so-called sigma-scaled sampling (SSS) which is running multiple Monte Carlo (MC) analysis with different scaling factors.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] In opposite to many other high yield estimation methods (like worst-case distances WCD) SSS does not suffer much from the dimensionality problem.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Also addressing multiple MC outputs causes no degradation in efficiency.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] On the other hand, as WCD, SSS is only designed for Gaussian statistical variables, and in opposite to WCD, the SSS method is not designed to provide accurate statistical corners.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Another SSS disadvantage is that the MC runs with large scale factors may become difficult, e. g. due to model and simulator convergence problems.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] In addition, in SSS we face a strong bias-variance trade-off: Using large scale factors, we obtain quite stable yield results, but the larger the scale factors, the larger the bias error.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] If the advantages of SSS does not matter much in the application of interest, then often other methods are more efficient.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Another simple and effective biasing technique employs translation of the density function (and hence random variable) to place much of its probability mass in the rare event region.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Translation does not suffer from a dimensionality effect and has been successfully used in several applications relating to simulation of digital communication systems.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] It often provides better simulation gains than scaling.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] where $c\,$ is the amount of shift and is to be chosen to minimize the variance of the importance sampling estimator.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] The fundamental problem with importance sampling is that designing good biased distributions becomes more complicated as the system complexity increases.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Complex systems are the systems with long memory since complex processing of a few inputs is much easier to handle.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] In principle, the importance sampling ideas remain the same in these situations, but the design becomes much harder.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] A successful approach to combat this problem is essentially breaking down a simulation into several smaller, more sharply defined subproblems.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Then importance sampling strategies are used to target each of the simpler subproblems.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Examples of techniques to break the simulation down are conditioning and error-event simulation (EES) and regenerative simulation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] In order to identify successful importance sampling techniques, it is useful to be able to quantify the run-time savings due to the use of the importance sampling approach.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] The performance measure commonly used is $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ , and this can be interpreted as the speed-up factor by which the importance sampling estimator achieves the same precision as the MC estimator.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] This has to be computed empirically since the estimator variances are not likely to be analytically possible when their mean is intractable.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Other useful concepts in quantifying an importance sampling estimator are the variance bounds and the notion of asymptotic efficiency.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] One related measure is the so-called **Effective Sample Size** **(ESS)**.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Variance is not the only possible cost function for a simulation, and other cost functions, such as the mean absolute deviation, are used in various statistical applications.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Nevertheless, the variance is the primary cost function addressed in the literature, probably due to the use of variances in confidence intervals and in the performance measure $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] An associated issue is the fact that the ratio $\sigma _{MC}^{2}/\sigma _{IS}^{2}\,$ overestimates the run-time savings due to importance sampling since it does not include the extra computing time required to compute the weight function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Hence, some people evaluate the net run-time improvement by various means.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Perhaps a more serious overhead to importance sampling is the time taken to devise and program the technique and analytically derive the desired weight function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] When different proposal distributions, $g_{i}(x)$ , $i=1,\ldots ,n,$ are jointly used for drawing the samples $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n},$ different proper weighting functions can be employed (e.g., see ).
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] In an adaptive setting, the proposal distributions, $g_{i,t}(x)$ , $i=1,\ldots ,n,$ and $t=1,\ldots ,T,$ are updated each iteration t of the adaptive importance sampling algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/importance-sampling] Hence, since a population of proposal densities is used, several suitable combinations of sampling and weighting schemes can be employed.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In statistics, **Markov chain Monte Carlo** (**MCMC**) is a class of algorithms used to draw samples from a probability distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Given a probability distribution, one can construct a Markov chain whose elements' distribution approximates it, i.e. the Markov chain's equilibrium distribution matches the target distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more steps that are included, the more closely the distribution of the sample matches the actual desired distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are used to study probability distributions that are too complex or too high dimensional to study with analytic techniques alone.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Various algorithms exist for constructing such Markov chains, including the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods create samples from a continuous random variable, with probability density proportional to a known function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These samples can be used to evaluate an integral over that variable, as its expected value or variance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Practically, an ensemble of chains is generally developed, starting from a set of points arbitrarily chosen and sufficiently distant from each other.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These chains are stochastic processes of "walkers" which move around randomly according to an algorithm that looks for places with a reasonably high contribution to the integral to move into next, assigning them higher probabilities.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Random walk Monte Carlo methods are a kind of random simulation or Monte Carlo method.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, whereas the random samples of the integrand used in a conventional Monte Carlo integration are statistically independent, those used in MCMC are autocorrelated.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Correlations of samples introduces the need to use the Markov chain central limit theorem when estimating the error of mean values.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms create Markov chains such that they have an equilibrium distribution which is proportional to the function given.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The development of MCMC methods is deeply rooted in the early exploration of Monte Carlo (MC) techniques in the mid-20th century, particularly in physics.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These developments were marked by the Metropolis algorithm proposed by Nicholas Metropolis, Arianna W.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Rosenbluth, Marshall Rosenbluth, Augusta H.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Teller, and Edward Teller in 1953, which was designed to tackle high-dimensional integration problems using early computers.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Hastings generalized this algorithm and inadvertently introduced the component-wise updating idea, later known as Gibbs sampling.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Simultaneously, the theoretical foundations for Gibbs sampling were being developed, such as the Hammersley–Clifford theorem from Julian Besag's 1974 paper.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Although the seeds of MCMC were sown earlier, including the formal naming of Gibbs sampling in image processing by Stuart Geman and Donald Geman (1984) and the data augmentation method by Martin A.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This transformation was accompanied by significant theoretical advancements, such as Luke Tierney's (1994) rigorous treatment of MCMC convergence, and Jun S.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Liu, Wong, and Augustine Kong's (1994, 1995) analysis of Gibbs sampler structure.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Subsequent developments further expanded the MCMC toolkit, including particle filters (Sequential Monte Carlo) for sequential problems, Perfect sampling aiming for exact simulation (Jim Propp and David B.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Green, 1995) for handling variable-dimension models, and deeper investigations into convergence diagnostics and the central limit theorem.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overall, the evolution of MCMC represents a paradigm shift in statistical computation, enabling the analysis of numerous previously intractable complex models and continually expanding the scope and impact of statistics.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose *(Xn)* is a Markov Chain in the general state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ with specific properties.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Particularly, we hope to establish the Law of Large Numbers and the Central Limit Theorem for MCMC.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the following, we state some definitions and theorems necessary for the important convergence results.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In short, we need the existence of invariant measure and Harris recurrent to establish the Law of Large Numbers of MCMC (Ergodic Theorem).
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] And we need aperiodicity, irreducibility and extra conditions such as reversibility to ensure the Central Limit Theorem holds in MCMC.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recall that in the discrete setting, a Markov chain is said to be *irreducible* if it is possible to reach any state from any other state in a finite number of steps with positive probability.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in the continuous setting, point-to-point transitions have zero probability.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, **φ-irreducibility** generalizes irreducibility by using a reference measure φ on the measurable space $({\mathcal {X}},{\mathcal {B}}({\mathcal {X}}))$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is a more general definition for irreducibility of a Markov chain in non-discrete state space.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the discrete case, an irreducible Markov chain is said to be *aperiodic* if it has period 1.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **Harris recurrent** if there exists a measure $\psi$ such that the chain is $\psi$ -irreducible and every measurable set A with $\psi (A)>0$ is Harris recurrent.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This definition is only needed when the state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ is uncountable.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the countable case, recurrence corresponds to $\mathbb {E} _{x}[\eta _{x}]=\infty$ , which is equivalent to $P_{x}(\tau _{x}<\infty )=1$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When there exists an *invariant probability measure* for a **ψ-irreducible** (hence recurrent) chain, the chain is said to be **positive recurrent**.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recurrent chains that do not allow for a finite invariant measure are called **null recurrent**.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In applications of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), a very useful criterion for Harris recurrence involves the use of bounded harmonic functions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These functions are *invariant* under the transition kernel in the functional sense, and they help characterize Harris recurrence.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This theorem provides a fundamental justification for the use of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, and it serves as the counterpart of the Law of Large Numbers (LLN) in classical Monte Carlo.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] An important aspect of this result is that $\pi$ does not need to be a probability measure.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Therefore, there can be some type of strong stability even if the chain is null recurrent.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Moreover, the Markov chain can be started from arbitrary state.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is the Ergodic Theorem that we are more familiar with.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are several conditions under which the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) holds for Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One of the most commonly used is the condition of **reversibility**.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A stationary Markov chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **reversible** if the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+2}=x$ is the same as the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n}=x$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] for every pair $(x,y)$ in the state space.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Even though reversibility is a restrictive assumption in theory, it is often easily satisfied in practical MCMC algorithms by introducing auxiliary variables or using symmetric proposal mechanisms.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are many other conditions that can be used to establish CLT for MCMC such as geometric ergodicity and the discrete state space.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods produce autocorrelated samples, in contrast to standard Monte Carlo techniques that draw independent samples.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Autocorrelation means successive draws from the Markov chain are statistically dependent, so each new sample adds less fresh information than an independent draw would.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As a result, one must account for this correlation when assessing the accuracy of estimates from the chain.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In particular, positive autocorrelation in the chain increases the variance of estimators and slows the convergence of sample averages toward the true expectation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effect of correlation on estimation can be quantified through the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For a chain targeting a distribution with variance $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of the sample mean after N steps is approximately ${\sigma ^{2}}{\big /}N_{\text{eff}}$ , where $N_{\text{eff}}$ is an effective sample size smaller than N .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The term in parentheses, $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}$ , is often called the integrated autocorrelation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When the chain has no autocorrelation ( $\rho _{k}=0$ for all $k\geq 1$ ), this factor equals 1, and one recovers the usual $\sigma ^{2}/N$ variance for independent samples.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the chain's samples are highly correlated, the sum of autocorrelations is large, leading to a much bigger variance for ${\bar {X}}_{N}$ than in the independent case.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effective sample size $N_{\text{eff}}$ is a useful diagnostic that translates the autocorrelation in a chain into an equivalent number of independent samples.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] so that $N_{\text{eff}}$ is the number of independent draws that would yield the same estimation precision as the N dependent draws from the Markov chain.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, if $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}=5$ , then $N_{\text{eff}}=N/5$ , meaning the chain of length N carries information equivalent to $N/5$ independent samples.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In an ideal scenario with no correlation, $\rho _{k}=0$ and thus $N_{\text{eff}}\approx N$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] But in a poorly mixing chain with strong autocorrelation, $N_{\text{eff}}$ can be much smaller than N .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, monitoring the ESS for each parameter is a way to gauge how much correlation is present: a low ESS indicates that many more iterations may be needed to achieve a desired effective sample of independent draws.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to address this problem could be shortening the steps of the walker, so that it does not continuously try to exit the highest probability region, though this way the process would be highly autocorrelated and expensive (i.e. many steps would be required for an accurate result).
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] More sophisticated methods such as Hamiltonian Monte Carlo and the Wang and Landau algorithm use various ways of reducing this autocorrelation, while managing to keep the process in the regions that give a higher contribution to the integral.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms usually rely on a more complicated theory and are harder to implement, but they usually converge faster.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] We outline several general strategies such as reparameterization, adaptive proposal tuning, parameter blocking, and overrelaxation that help reduce correlation and improve sampling efficiency within the standard MCMC framework.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to reduce autocorrelation is to reformulate or reparameterize the statistical model so that the posterior geometry leads to more efficient sampling.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By changing the coordinate system or using alternative variable definitions, one can often lessen correlations.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, in Bayesian hierarchical modeling, a non-centered parameterization can be used in place of the standard (centered) formulation to avoid extreme posterior correlations between latent and higher-level parameters.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This involves expressing latent variables in terms of independent auxiliary variables, dramatically improving mixing.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Such reparameterization strategies are commonly employed in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithm to enhance convergence and reduce autocorrelation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Another approach to reducing correlation is to improve the MCMC proposal mechanism.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, step size tuning is critical: if the proposed steps are too small, the sampler moves slowly and produces highly correlated samples; if the steps are too large, many proposals are rejected, resulting in repeated values.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adjusting the proposal step size during an initial testing phase helps find a balance where the sampler explores the space efficiently without too many rejections.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adaptive MCMC methods modify proposal distributions based on the chain's past samples.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, the adaptive Metropolis algorithm updates the Gaussian proposal distribution using the full information accumulated from the chain so far, allowing the proposal to adapt over time.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is a technique that reduces autocorrelation in MCMC by updating parameters jointly rather than one at a time.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When parameters exhibit strong posterior correlations, one-by-one updates can lead to poor mixing and slow exploration of the target distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By identifying and sampling blocks of correlated parameters together, the sampler can more effectively traverse high-density regions of the posterior.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is commonly used in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithms.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In blocked Gibbs sampling, entire groups of variables are updated conditionally at each step.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings, multivariate proposals enable joint updates (i.e., updates of multiple parameters at once using a vector-valued proposal distribution, typically a multivariate Gaussian), though they often require careful tuning of the proposal covariance matrix.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is a technique to reduce autocorrelation between successive samples by proposing new samples that are negatively correlated with the current state.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This helps the chain explore the posterior more efficiently, especially in high-dimensional Gaussian models or when using Gibbs sampling.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The basic idea is to reflect the current sample across the conditional mean, producing proposals that retain the correct stationary distribution but with reduced serial dependence.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is particularly effective when combined with Gaussian conditional distributions, where exact reflection or partial overrelaxation can be analytically implemented.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting MCMC methodologies are a class of mean-field particle methods for obtaining random samples from a sequence of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In principle, any Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler can be turned into an interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers can be interpreted as a way to run in parallel a sequence of Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, interacting simulated annealing algorithms are based on independent Metropolis–Hastings moves interacting sequentially with a selection-resampling type mechanism.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In contrast to traditional Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, the precision parameter of this class of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers is *only* related to the number of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These advanced particle methodologies belong to the class of Feynman–Kac particle models, also called Sequential Monte Carlo or particle filter methods in Bayesian inference and signal processing communities.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mutation-selection genetic particle algorithm with Markov chain Monte Carlo mutations.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The quasi-Monte Carlo method is an analog to the normal Monte Carlo method that uses low-discrepancy sequences instead of random numbers.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] It yields an integration error that decays faster than that of true random sampling, as quantified by the Koksma–Hlawka inequality.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Empirically it allows the reduction of both estimation error and convergence time by an order of magnitude.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain quasi-Monte Carlo methods such as the Array–RQMC method combine randomized quasi–Monte Carlo and Markov chain simulation by simulating n chains simultaneously in a way that better approximates the true distribution of the chain than with ordinary MCMC.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In empirical experiments, the variance of the average of a function of the state sometimes converges at rate $O(n^{-2})$ or even faster, instead of the $O(n^{-1})$ Monte Carlo rate.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods are primarily used for calculating numerical approximations of multi-dimensional integrals, for example in Bayesian statistics, computational physics, computational biology and computational linguistics.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Bayesian statistics, Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are typically used to calculate moments and credible intervals of posterior probability distributions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The use of MCMC methods makes it possible to compute large hierarchical models that require integrations over hundreds to thousands of unknown parameters.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Many contemporary research problems in statistical physics can be addressed by approximate solutions using Monte Carlo simulation, which provides valuable insights into the properties of complex systems.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Monte Carlo methods are fundamental in computational physics, astrophysics, physical chemistry, and related disciplines, with broad applications including medical physics, where they are employed to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead of exhaustively analyzing all possible system states, the Monte Carlo method randomly examines a subset of them to form a representative sample, and yields accurate approximations of the system's characteristic properties.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As the number of sampled states increases, the error can be further reduced to a lower level.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Langevin Dynamics are typically used in complex distribution sampling and generative modeling, via an MCMC procedure.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Specifically, given the probability density function $p(x)$ , we use its log gradient $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ as the score function and start from a prior distribution $x_{0}\sim p_{0}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$ and $K\rightarrow \infty$ , $x_{K}$ converges to a sample from the target distribution $p(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For some complex distribution, if we know its probability density function but find it difficult to directly sample from it, we can apply Langevin Dynamics as an alternate.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in most cases, especially generative modeling, usually we do not know the exact probability density function of the target distribution we wish to sample from, neither the score function $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, score matching methods provide feasible solutions, minimizing the Fisher information metric between a parameterized score-based model $s_{\theta }(x)$ and the score function without knowing the ground-truth data score.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The score function can be estimated on a training dataset by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In real cases, however, the training data only takes a small region of the target distribution, and the estimated score functions are inaccurate in other low density regions with fewer available data examples.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] To overcome this challenge, denoising score matching methods perturb the available data examples with noise of different scales, which can improve the coverage of low density regions, and use them as the training dataset for the score-base model.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Note that the choice of noise scales is tricky, as too large noise will corrupt the original data, while too small noise will not populate the original data to those low density regions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Thus, carefully crafted noise schedules are applied for higher quality generation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Usually it is not hard to construct a Markov chain with the desired properties.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more difficult problem is to determine (1) when to start collecting statistics and (2) how many steps are needed to converge to the stationary distribution within an acceptable error.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Fortunately, there are a variety of practical diagnostics to empirically assess convergence.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Formally, let $\pi$ denote the stationary distribution and $P^{t}(x,\cdot )$ the distribution of the Markov chain after t steps starting from state x .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A chain is said to mix rapidly if $d_{\text{TV}}(P^{t}(x,\cdot ),\pi )\leq \epsilon$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ within a small number of steps t under a pre-defined tolerance $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In other words, the stationary distribution is reached quickly starting from an arbitrary position, and the minimum such t is known as the mixing time.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, however, the total variation distance is generally intractable to compute, especially in high-dimensional problems or when the stationary distribution is only known up to a normalizing constant (as in most Bayesian applications).
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Gelman-Rubin statistic, also known as the **potential scale reduction factor (PSRF)**, evaluates MCMC convergence by sampling multiple independent Markov chains and comparing within-chain and between-chain variances.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If all chains have converged to the same stationary distribution, the between-chain and within-chain variances should be similar, and thus the PSRF must approach 1.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, a value of $<1.1$ is often taken as evidence of convergence.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Higher values suggest that the chains are still exploring different parts of the target distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Geweke diagnostic examines whether the distribution of samples in the early part of the Markov chain is statistically indistinguishable from the distribution in a later part.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Since MCMC samples are autocorrelated, a simple comparison of sample means is insufficient.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead, the difference in means is standardized using an estimator of the spectral density at zero frequency, which accounts for the long-range dependencies in the chain.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the long-run variance (i.e., the spectral density at frequency zero), commonly estimated using Newey-West estimators or batch means.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the statistic Z follows an approximately standard normal distribution $Z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If $|Z|>1.96$ , the null hypothesis is rejected at the 5% significance level, suggesting that the chain has not yet reached stationarity.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Heidelberger-Welch diagnostic is grounded in spectral analysis and Brownian motion theory, and is particularly useful in the early stages of simulation to determine appropriate burn-in and stopping time.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The diagnostic consists of two components, a **stationarity test** that assesses whether the Markov chain has reached a steady-state, and a **half-width test** that determines whether the estimated expectation is within a user-specified precision.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let $\{X_{t}\}_{t=1}^{n}$ be the output of an MCMC simulation for a scalar function $g(X_{t})$ , and $g_{1},g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}$ the evaluations of the function g over the chain.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\bar {g}}_{n}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}g_{i}$ is the sample mean and ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the spectral density at frequency zero.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the process $B_{n}(t)$ converges in distribution to a Brownian bridge.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This statistic is compared against known critical values from the Brownian bridge distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the null hypothesis is rejected, the first 10% of the samples are discarded and the test can be repeated on the remaining chain until either stationarity is accepted or 50% of the chain is discarded.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Once stationarity is accepted, the second part of the diagnostic checks whether the Monte Carlo estimator is accurate enough for practical use.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ is an estimate of the variance of $g(X)$ , $t_{\alpha /2,\nu }$ is the Student's t critical value at confidence level $1-\alpha$ and degrees of freedom $\nu$ , n is the number of samples used.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the half-width is smaller than a user-defined tolerance (e.g., 0.05), the chain is considered long enough to estimate the expectation reliably.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Otherwise, the simulation should be extended.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is specifically designed to assess how many iterations are needed to estimate quantiles or tail probabilities of the target distribution with a desired accuracy and confidence.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Unlike Gelman-Rubin or Geweke diagnostics, which are based on assessing convergence to the entire distribution, the Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is goal-oriented as it provides estimates for the number of samples required to estimate a specific quantile of interest within a desired margin of error.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let q denote the desired quantile (e.g., 0.025) of a real-valued function $g(X)$ : in other words, the goal is to find u such that $P(g(X)\leq u)=q$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose we wish to estimate this quantile such that the estimate falls within margin $\varepsilon$ of the true value with probability $1-\alpha$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $I(\cdot )$ is the indicator function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The sequence $\{W_{n}\}$ is treated as a realization from a two-state Markov chain.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] While this may not be strictly true, it is often a good approximation in practice.
[src:metropolis-hastings/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $\Phi ^{-1}(\cdot )$ is the standard normal quantile function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In statistics and statistical physics, the **Metropolis–Hastings algorithm** is a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) method for obtaining a sequence of random samples from a probability distribution from which direct sampling is difficult.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] New samples are added to the sequence in two steps: first a new sample is proposed based on the previous sample, then the proposed sample is either added to the sequence or rejected depending on the value of the probability distribution at that point.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The resulting sequence can be used to approximate the distribution (e.g. to generate a histogram) or to compute an integral (e.g. an expected value).
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis–Hastings and other MCMC algorithms are generally used for sampling from multi-dimensional distributions, especially when the number of dimensions is high.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For single-dimensional distributions, there are usually other methods (e.g. adaptive rejection sampling) that can directly return independent samples from the distribution, and these are free from the problem of autocorrelated samples that is inherent in MCMC methods.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The algorithm is named in part for Nicholas Metropolis, the first coauthor of a 1953 paper, entitled *Equation of State Calculations by Fast Computing Machines*, with Arianna W.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For many years the algorithm was known simply as the *Metropolis algorithm*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The paper proposed the algorithm for the case of symmetrical proposal distributions, but in 1970, W.K.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Hastings extended it to the more general case.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The generalized method was eventually identified by both names, although the first use of the term "Metropolis-Hastings algorithm" is unclear.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Some controversy exists with regard to credit for development of the Metropolis algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis, who was familiar with the computational aspects of the method, had coined the term "Monte Carlo" in an earlier article with Stanisław Ulam, and led the group in the Theoretical Division that designed and built the MANIAC I computer used in the experiments in 1952.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] However, prior to 2003 there was no detailed account of the algorithm's development.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Shortly before his death, Marshall Rosenbluth attended a 2003 conference at LANL marking the 50th anniversary of the 1953 publication.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] At this conference, Rosenbluth described the algorithm and its development in a presentation titled "Genesis of the Monte Carlo Algorithm for Statistical Mechanics".
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Further historical clarification is made by Gubernatis in a 2005 journal article recounting the 50th anniversary conference.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Rosenbluth makes it clear that he and his wife Arianna did the work, and that Metropolis played no role in the development other than providing computer time.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This contradicts an account by Edward Teller, who states in his memoirs that the five authors of the 1953 article worked together for "days (and nights)".
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In contrast, the detailed account by Rosenbluth credits Teller with a crucial but early suggestion to "take advantage of statistical mechanics and take ensemble averages instead of following detailed kinematics".
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This, says Rosenbluth, started him thinking about the generalized Monte Carlo approach – a topic which he says he had discussed often with John Von Neumann.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Arianna Rosenbluth recounted (to Gubernatis in 2003) that Augusta Teller started the computer work, but that Arianna herself took it over and wrote the code from scratch.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In an oral history recorded shortly before his death, Rosenbluth again credits Teller with posing the original problem, himself with solving it, and Arianna with programming the computer.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can draw samples from any probability distribution with probability density $P(x)$ , provided that we know a function $f(x)$ proportional to the density P and the values of $f(x)$ can be calculated.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The requirement that $f(x)$ must only be proportional to the density, rather than exactly equal to it, makes the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm particularly useful, because it removes the need to calculate the density's normalization factor, which is often extremely difficult in practice.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm generates a sequence of sample values in such a way that, as more and more sample values are produced, the distribution of values more closely approximates the desired distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These sample values are produced iteratively in such a way, that the distribution of the next sample depends only on the current sample value, which makes the sequence of samples a Markov chain.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Specifically, at each iteration, the algorithm proposes a candidate for the next sample value based on the current sample value.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Then, with some probability, the candidate is either accepted, in which case the candidate value is used in the next iteration, or it is rejected in which case the candidate value is discarded, and the current value is reused in the next iteration.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The probability of acceptance is determined by comparing the values of the function $f(x)$ of the current and candidate sample values with respect to the desired distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The method used to propose new candidates is characterized by the probability distribution $g(x\mid y)$ (sometimes written $Q(x\mid y)$ ) of a new proposed sample x given the previous sample y .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is called the *proposal density*, *proposal function*, or *jumping distribution*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A common choice for $g(x\mid y)$ is a Gaussian distribution centered at y , so that points closer to y are more likely to be visited next, making the sequence of samples into a Gaussian random walk.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In the original paper by Metropolis et al.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] (1953), $g(x\mid y)$ was suggested to be a uniform distribution limited to some maximum distance from y .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] More complicated proposal functions are also possible, such as those of Hamiltonian Monte Carlo, Langevin Monte Carlo, or preconditioned Crank–Nicolson.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For the purpose of illustration, the Metropolis algorithm, a special case of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm where the proposal function is symmetric, is described below.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Let $f(x)$ be a function that is proportional to the desired probability density function $P(x)$ (a.k.a. a target distribution).
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This algorithm proceeds by randomly attempting to move about the sample space, sometimes accepting the moves and sometimes remaining in place. $P(x)$ at specific point x is proportional to the iterations spent on the point by the algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Note that the acceptance ratio $\alpha$ indicates how probable the new proposed sample is with respect to the current sample, according to the distribution whose density is $P(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If we attempt to move to a point that is more probable than the existing point (i.e. a point in a higher-density region of $P(x)$ corresponding to an $\alpha >1\geq u$ ), we will always accept the move.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] However, if we attempt to move to a less probable point, we will sometimes reject the move, and the larger the relative drop in probability, the more likely we are to reject the new point.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Thus, we will tend to stay in (and return large numbers of samples from) high-density regions of $P(x)$ , while only occasionally visiting low-density regions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Intuitively, this is why this algorithm works and returns samples that follow the desired distribution with density $P(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] On the other hand, most simple rejection sampling methods suffer from the "curse of dimensionality", where the probability of rejection increases exponentially as a function of the number of dimensions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis–Hastings, along with other MCMC methods, do not have this problem to such a degree, and thus are often the only solutions available when the number of dimensions of the distribution to be sampled is high.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] As a result, MCMC methods are often the methods of choice for producing samples from hierarchical Bayesian models and other high-dimensional statistical models used nowadays in many disciplines.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In multivariate distributions, the classic Metropolis–Hastings algorithm as described above involves choosing a new multi-dimensional sample point.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] When the number of dimensions is high, finding the suitable jumping distribution to use can be difficult, as the different individual dimensions behave in very different ways, and the jumping width (see above) must be "just right" for all dimensions at once to avoid excessively slow mixing.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] An alternative approach that often works better in such situations, known as Gibbs sampling, involves choosing a new sample for each dimension separately from the others, rather than choosing a sample for all dimensions at once.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] That way, the problem of sampling from potentially high-dimensional space will be reduced to a collection of problems to sample from small dimensionality.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is especially applicable when the multivariate distribution is composed of a set of individual random variables in which each variable is conditioned on only a small number of other variables, as is the case in most typical hierarchical models.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The individual variables are then sampled one at a time, with each variable conditioned on the most recent values of all the others.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The purpose of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is to generate a collection of states according to a desired distribution $P(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] To accomplish this, the algorithm uses a Markov process, which asymptotically reaches a unique stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ such that $\pi (x)=P(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A Markov process is uniquely defined by its transition probabilities $P(x'\mid x)$ , the probability of transitioning from any given state x to any other given state $x'$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] *Uniqueness of stationary distribution*: the stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ must be unique.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is guaranteed by ergodicity of the Markov process, which requires that every state must (1) be aperiodic—the system does not return to the same state at fixed intervals; and (2) be positive recurrent—the expected number of steps for returning to the same state is finite.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm involves designing a Markov process (by constructing transition probabilities) that fulfills the two above conditions, such that its stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ is chosen to be $P(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The approach is to separate the transition in two sub-steps; the proposal and the acceptance-rejection.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The proposal distribution $g(x'\mid x)$ is the conditional probability of proposing a state $x'$ given x , and the acceptance distribution $A(x',x)$ is the probability to accept the proposed state $x'$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The next step in the derivation is to choose an acceptance ratio that fulfills the condition above.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For this Metropolis acceptance ratio A , either $A(x',x)=1$ or $A(x,x')=1$ and, either way, the condition is satisfied.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] 3. if $u>A(x',x_{t})$ , then *reject* the new state, and copy the old state forward $x_{t+1}=x_{t}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Provided that specified conditions are met, the empirical distribution of saved states $x_{0},\ldots ,x_{T}$ will approach $P(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The number of iterations ( T ) required to effectively estimate $P(x)$ depends on the number of factors, including the relationship between $P(x)$ and the proposal distribution and the desired accuracy of estimation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For distribution on discrete state spaces, it has to be of the order of the autocorrelation time of the Markov process.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] An accessible account of the convergence theory for Metropolis–Hastings is given in.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] It is important to notice that it is not clear, in a general problem, which distribution $g(x'\mid x)$ one should use or the number of iterations necessary for proper estimation; both are free parameters of the method, which must be adjusted to the particular problem in hand.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A common use of Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is to compute an integral.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Specifically, consider a space $\Omega \subset \mathbb {R}$ and a probability distribution $P(x)$ over $\Omega$ , $x\in \Omega$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] where $A(x)$ is a (measurable) function of interest.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For example, consider a statistic $E(x)$ and its probability distribution $P(E)$ , which is a marginal distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Suppose that the goal is to estimate $P(E)$ for E on the tail of $P(E)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] and, thus, estimating $P(E)$ can be accomplished by estimating the expected value of the indicator function $A_{E}(x)\equiv \mathbf {1} _{E}(x)$ , which is 1 when $E(x)\in [E,E+\Delta E]$ and zero otherwise.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Because E is on the tail of $P(E)$ , the probability to draw a state x with $E(x)$ on the tail of $P(E)$ is proportional to $P(E)$ , which is small by definition.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can be used here to sample (rare) states more likely and thus increase the number of samples used to estimate $P(E)$ on the tails.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This can be done e.g. by using a sampling distribution $\pi (x)$ to favor those states (e.g. $\pi (x)\propto e^{aE}$ with $a>0$ ).
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Suppose that the most recent value sampled is $x_{t}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] is the ratio of the proposal density in two directions (from $x_{t}$ to $x'$ and conversely).
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is equal to 1 if the proposal density is symmetric.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Then the new state $x_{t+1}$ is chosen according to the following rules.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Markov chain is started from an arbitrary initial value $x_{0}$ , and the algorithm is run for many iterations until this initial state is "forgotten".
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These samples, which are discarded, are known as *burn-in*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The remaining set of accepted values of x represent a sample from the distribution $P(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The algorithm works best if the proposal density matches the shape of the target distribution $P(x)$ , from which direct sampling is difficult, that is $g(x'\mid x_{t})\approx P(x')$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If a Gaussian proposal density g is used, the variance parameter $\sigma ^{2}$ has to be tuned during the burn-in period.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is usually done by calculating the *acceptance rate*, which is the fraction of proposed samples that is accepted in a window of the last N samples.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The desired acceptance rate depends on the target distribution, however it has been shown theoretically that the ideal acceptance rate for a one-dimensional Gaussian distribution is about 50%, decreasing to about 23% for an N -dimensional Gaussian target distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These guidelines can work well when sampling from sufficiently regular Bayesian posteriors as they often follow a multivariate normal distribution as can be established using the Bernstein–von Mises theorem.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If $\sigma ^{2}$ is too small, the chain will *mix slowly* (i.e., the acceptance rate will be high, but successive samples will move around the space slowly, and the chain will converge only slowly to $P(x)$ ).
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] On the other hand, if $\sigma ^{2}$ is too large, the acceptance rate will be very low because the proposals are likely to land in regions of much lower probability density, so $a_{1}$ will be very small, and again the chain will converge very slowly.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] One typically tunes the proposal distribution so that the algorithms accepts on the order of 30% of all samples – in line with the theoretical estimates mentioned in the previous paragraph.
[src:metropolis-hastings/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] MCMC can be used to draw samples from the posterior distribution of a statistical model.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In mathematics, a **random walk** is a stochastic process that describes a path that consists of a succession of random steps on some mathematical space.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] An elementary example of a random walk is one on the integer number line $\mathbb {Z}$ which starts at 0, and at each step moves +1 or −1 with equal probability.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Other examples include the path traced by a molecule as it travels in a liquid or a gas (see Brownian motion), the search path of a foraging animal, or the price of a fluctuating stock and the financial status of a gambler.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Random walks have applications to engineering and many scientific fields including ecology, psychology, computer science, physics, chemistry, biology, economics, and sociology.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The term *random walk* was first introduced by Karl Pearson in 1905.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Realizations of random walks can be obtained by Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In certain contexts random walk is sometimes known as a **drunkard's walk**.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A popular random walk model is that of a random walk on a regular lattice, where at each step the location jumps to another site according to some probability distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In a *simple random walk*, the location can only jump to neighboring sites of the lattice, forming a lattice path.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In a *simple symmetric random walk* on a locally finite lattice, the probabilities of the location jumping to each one of its immediate neighbors are the same.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The best-studied example is the random walk on the *d*-dimensional integer lattice (sometimes called the hypercubic lattice) $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] If, in addition, the state space is finite, the random walk model is called a *simple bordered symmetric random walk*, and the transition probabilities depend on the location of the state because on margin and corner states the movement is limited.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] An elementary example of a random walk is the random walk on the integer number line, $\mathbb {Z}$ , which starts at 0 and at each step moves +1 or −1 with equal probability.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This walk can be illustrated as follows.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A marker is placed at zero on the number line, and a fair coin is flipped.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] If it lands on heads, the marker is moved one unit to the right.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] If it lands on tails, the marker is moved one unit to the left.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] After five flips, the marker could now be on -5, -3, -1, 1, 3, 5.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] With five flips, three heads and two tails, in any order, it will land on 1.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] See the figure below for an illustration of the possible outcomes of 5 flips.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This series (the sum of the sequence of −1s and 1s) gives the net distance walked, if each part of the walk is of length one.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] That is, the mean of all coin flips approaches zero as the number of flips increases.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This hints that $E(|S_{n}|)\,\!$ , the expected translation distance after *n* steps, should be of the order of ${\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] To answer the question of how many times will a random walk cross a boundary line if permitted to continue walking forever, a simple random walk on $\mathbb {Z}$ will cross every point an infinite number of times.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This result has many names: the *level-crossing phenomenon*, *recurrence* or the *gambler's ruin*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The reason for the last name is as follows: a gambler with a finite amount of money will eventually lose when playing *a fair game* against a bank with an infinite amount of money.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The gambler's money will perform a random walk, and it will reach zero at some point, and the game will be over.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] If *a* and *b* are positive integers, then the expected number of steps until a one-dimensional simple random walk starting at 0 first hits *b* or −*a* is *ab*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The probability that this walk will hit *b* before −*a* is $a/(a+b)$ , which can be derived from the fact that simple random walk is a martingale.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] And these expectations and hitting probabilities can be computed in $O(a+b)$ in the general one-dimensional random walk Markov chain.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Some of the results mentioned above can be derived from properties of Pascal's triangle.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The number of different walks of *n* steps where each step is +1 or −1 is 2*n*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] For the simple random walk, each of these walks is equally likely.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In order for *Sn* to be equal to a number *k* it is necessary and sufficient that the number of +1 in the walk exceeds those of −1 by *k*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] It follows +1 must appear (*n* + *k*)/2 times among *n* steps of a walk, hence the number of walks which satisfy $S_{n}=k$ equals the number of ways of choosing (*n* + *k*)/2 elements from an *n* element set, denoted ${\textstyle n \choose (n+k)/2}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] For this to have meaning, it is necessary that *n* + *k* be an even number, which implies *n* and *k* are either both even or both odd.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Therefore, the probability that $S_{n}=k$ is equal to ${\textstyle 2^{-n}{n \choose (n+k)/2}}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] By representing entries of Pascal's triangle in terms of factorials and using Stirling's formula, one can obtain good estimates for these probabilities for large values of n .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This relation with Pascal's triangle is demonstrated for small values of *n*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] At zero turns, the only possibility will be to remain at zero.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] However, at one turn, there is one chance of landing on −1 or one chance of landing on 1.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] At two turns, a marker at 1 could move to 2 or back to zero.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A marker at −1, could move to −2 or back to zero.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Therefore, there is one chance of landing on −2, two chances of landing on zero, and one chance of landing on 2.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The central limit theorem and the law of the iterated logarithm describe important aspects of the behavior of simple random walks on $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In particular, the former entails that as *n* increases, the probabilities (proportional to the numbers in each row) approach a normal distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] taking the limit (and observing that ${\textstyle {1}/{\sqrt {n}}}$ corresponds to the spacing of the scaling grid) one finds the gaussian density ${\textstyle f(x)={\frac {1}{2{\sqrt {\pi }}}}e^{-{x^{2}}}}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Indeed, for a absolutely continuous random variable ${\textstyle X}$ with density ${\textstyle f_{X}}$ it holds ${\textstyle \mathbb {P} \left(X\in [x,x+dx)\right)=f_{X}(x)dx}$ , with ${\textstyle dx}$ corresponding to an infinitesimal spacing.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] As a direct generalization, one can consider random walks on crystal lattices (infinite-fold abelian covering graphs over finite graphs).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Actually it is possible to establish the central limit theorem and large deviation theorem in this setting.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The heterogeneous random walk draws in each time step a random number that determines the local jumping probabilities and then a random number that determines the actual jump direction.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The main question is the probability of staying in each of the various sites after t jumps, and in the limit of this probability when t is very large.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In higher dimensions, the set of randomly walked points has interesting geometric properties.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In fact, one gets a discrete fractal, that is, a set which exhibits stochastic self-similarity on large scales.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] On small scales, one can observe "jaggedness" resulting from the grid on which the walk is performed.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The trajectory of a random walk is the collection of points visited, considered as a set with disregard to *when* the walk arrived at the point.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In one dimension, the trajectory is simply all points between the minimum height and the maximum height the walk achieved (both are, on average, on the order of ${\sqrt {n}}$ ).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] To visualize the two-dimensional case, one can imagine a person walking randomly around a city.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The city is effectively infinite and arranged in a square grid of sidewalks.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] At every intersection, the person randomly chooses one of the four possible routes (including the one originally travelled from).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Formally, this is a random walk on the set of all points in the plane with integer coordinates.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] To answer the question of the person ever getting back to the original starting point of the walk, this is the 2-dimensional equivalent of the level-crossing problem discussed above.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In 1921 George Pólya proved that the person almost surely would in a 2-dimensional random walk, but for 3 dimensions or higher, the probability of returning to the origin decreases as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In 3 dimensions, the probability decreases to roughly 34%.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The mathematician Shizuo Kakutani was known to refer to this result with the following quote: "A drunk man will find his way home, but a drunk bird may get lost forever".
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Paul Erdős and Samuel James Taylor also showed in 1960 that for dimensions less or equal than 4, two independent random walks starting from any two given points have infinitely many intersections almost surely, but for dimensions higher than 5, they almost surely intersect only finitely often.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The asymptotic function for a two-dimensional random walk as the number of steps increases is given by a Rayleigh distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The probability distribution is a function of the radius from the origin and the step length is constant for each step.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Here, the step length is assumed to be 1, N is the total number of steps and r is the radius from the origin.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A Wiener process is a stochastic process with similar behavior to Brownian motion, the physical phenomenon of a minute particle diffusing in a fluid.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A Wiener process is the scaling limit of random walk in dimension 1.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This means that if there is a random walk with very small steps, there is an approximation to a Wiener process (and, less accurately, to Brownian motion).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] To be more precise, if the step size is ε, one needs to take a walk of length *L*/ε2 to approximate a Wiener length of *L*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] As the step size tends to 0 (and the number of steps increases proportionally), random walk converges to a Wiener process in an appropriate sense.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Formally, if *B* is the space of all paths of length *L* with the maximum topology, and if *M* is the space of measure over *B* with the norm topology, then the convergence is in the space *M*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Similarly, a Wiener process in several dimensions is the scaling limit of random walk in the same number of dimensions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A random walk is a discrete fractal (a function with integer dimensions; 1, 2, ...), but a Wiener process trajectory is a true fractal, and there is a connection between the two.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] For example, take a random walk until it hits a circle of radius *r* times the step length.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The average number of steps it performs is *r*2.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This fact is the *discrete version* of the fact that a Wiener process walk is a fractal of Hausdorff dimension 2.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In two dimensions, the average number of points the same random walk has on the *boundary* of its trajectory is *r*4/3.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This corresponds to the fact that the boundary of the trajectory of a Wiener process is a fractal of dimension 4/3, a fact predicted by Mandelbrot using simulations but proved only in 2000 by Lawler, Schramm and Werner.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A Wiener process enjoys many symmetries a random walk does not.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] For example, a Wiener process walk is invariant to rotations, but the random walk is not, since the underlying grid is not (random walk is invariant to rotations by 90 degrees, but Wiener processes are invariant to rotations by, for example, 17 degrees too).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This means that in many cases, problems on a random walk are easier to solve by translating them to a Wiener process, solving the problem there, and then translating back.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] On the other hand, some problems are easier to solve with random walks due to its discrete nature.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Random walk and Wiener process can be *coupled*, namely manifested on the same probability space in a dependent way that forces them to be quite close.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The simplest such coupling is the Skorokhod embedding, but there exist more precise couplings, such as Komlós–Major–Tusnády approximation theorem.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The convergence of a random walk toward the Wiener process is controlled by the central limit theorem, and by Donsker's theorem.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] where *t* is the time elapsed since the start of the random walk, $\varepsilon$ is the size of a step of the random walk, and $\delta t$ is the time elapsed between two successive steps.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This corresponds to the Green's function of the diffusion equation that controls the Wiener process, which suggests that, after a large number of steps, the random walk converges toward a Wiener process.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The two expressions of the variance above correspond to the distribution associated to the vector ${\vec {R}}$ that links the two ends of the random walk, in 3D.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The variance associated to each component $R_{x}$ , $R_{y}$ or $R_{z}$ is only one third of this value (still in 3D).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A random walk having a step size that varies according to a normal distribution ${\mathcal {N}}(\mu ,\sigma ^{2})$ , $\mu$ being the mean and $\sigma$ being the standard deviation, is used as a model for real-world time-series data such as financial markets.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Here, the step size is given by the inverse cumulative normal distribution $\Phi ^{-1}(x,\mu ,\sigma ),$ where $x\in \{0,1\}$ is a uniformly distributed random number.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] If $\mu$ is nonzero, the random walk will vary about a linear trend.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] If $v_{s}$ is the starting value of the random walk, the expected value after n steps will be $v_{s}+n\mu$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] But for the Gaussian random walk, this is just the standard deviation of the translation distance's distribution after n steps.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Hence, if $\mu =0$ , and since the root mean square (RMS) translation distance is one standard deviation, there is a 68.27% probability that the RMS translation distance after n steps will fall between $\pm \sigma {\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The number of distinct sites visited by a single random walker $S(t)$ has been studied extensively for square and cubic lattices and for fractals.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This quantity is useful for the analysis of problems of trapping and kinetic reactions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] It is also related to the vibrational density of states, diffusion reactions processes and spread of populations in ecology.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Therefore, it is impossible to encode ${\{Z_{n}\}_{n=1}^{N}}$ using a binary code of less than $NR(D_{\theta })$ bits and recover it with expected mean squared error less than $D_{\theta }$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In financial economics, the random walk hypothesis is used to model share prices and other factors.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Empirical studies found some deviations from this theoretical model, especially in short term and long term correlations.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In semiconductor manufacturing, random walks are used to analyze the effects of thermal treatment at smaller nodes.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] It is applied to understand the diffusion of dopants, defects and other impurities during the critical fabrication steps.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Random walk treatments are also used to study the diffusion of reactants, products and plasma during chemical vapor deposition processes.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Continuum diffusion has been used to study the flow of gases, at macroscopic scales, in CVD reactors.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] However, smaller dimensions and increased complexity has forced us to treat them with random walk.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This allows for accurate analysis of stochastic processes, at molecular level and smaller, in semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In computer science, random walks have been used to estimate the size of the Web.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In computer programming it is possible to calculate pi with a random walk.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Random walks have been used in network analysis to calculate the probability two unlinked nodes will be linked in the future based on the current state of the network.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Various algorithms are discussed in including PageRank and supervised random walks.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In image segmentation, random walks are used to determine the labels (i.e., "object" or "background") to associate with each pixel.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This algorithm is typically referred to as the random walker segmentation algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The Twitter website used random walks to make suggestions of whom to follow.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] As mentioned, the range of natural phenomena which have been subject to attempts at description by some flavour of random walks is considerable.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This is particularly the case in the fields of physics, chemistry, materials science, and biology.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A number of types of stochastic processes have been considered that are similar to the pure random walks but where the simple structure is allowed to be more generalized.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The *pure* structure can be characterized by the steps being defined by independent and identically distributed random variables.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Random walks can take place on a variety of spaces, such as graphs, the integers, the real line, the plane or higher-dimensional vector spaces, on curved surfaces or higher-dimensional Riemannian manifolds, and on groups.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] It is also possible to define random walks which take their steps at random times, and in that case, the position X t has to be defined for all times *t* ∈ [0, +∞).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Specific cases or limits of random walks include the Lévy flight and diffusion models such as Brownian motion.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A random walk of length *k* on a possibly infinite graph *G* with a root *0* is a stochastic process with random variables $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{k}$ such that $X_{1}=0$ and ${X_{i+1}}$ is a vertex chosen uniformly at random from the neighbors of $X_{i}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Then the number $p_{v,w,k}(G)$ is the probability that a random walk of length *k* starting at *v* ends at *w*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In particular, if *G* is a graph with root *0*, $p_{0,0,2k}$ is the probability that a $2k$ -step random walk returns to *0*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Building on the analogy from the earlier section on higher dimensions, assume now that our city is no longer a perfect square grid.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] When our person reaches a certain junction, he picks between the variously available roads with equal probability.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Thus, if the junction has seven exits the person will go to each one with probability one-seventh.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] It turns out that under rather mild conditions, the answer is still yes, but depending on the graph, the answer to the variant question 'Will two persons meet again?' may not be that they meet infinitely often almost surely.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] An example of a case where the person will reach his home almost surely is when the lengths of all the blocks are between *a* and *b* (where *a* and *b* are any two finite positive numbers).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Notice that we do not assume that the graph is planar, i.e. the city may contain tunnels and bridges.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] One way to prove this result is using the connection to electrical networks.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Take a map of the city and place a one ohm resistor on every block.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Now measure the "resistance between a point and infinity".
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In other words, choose some number *R* and take all the points in the electrical network with distance bigger than *R* from our point and wire them together.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This is now a finite electrical network, and we may measure the resistance from our point to the wired points.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The limit is called the *resistance between a point and infinity*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In other words, in a transient system, one only needs to overcome a finite resistance to get to infinity from any point.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In a recurrent system, the resistance from any point to infinity is infinite.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This characterization of transience and recurrence is very useful, and specifically it allows us to analyze the case of a city drawn in the plane with the distances bounded.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A random walk on a graph is a very special case of a Markov chain.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Unlike a general Markov chain, random walk on a graph enjoys a property called *time symmetry* or *reversibility*.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Roughly speaking, this property, also called the principle of detailed balance, means that the probabilities to traverse a given path in one direction or the other have a very simple connection between them (if the graph is regular, they are just equal).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This property has important consequences.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Starting in the 1980s, much research has gone into connecting properties of the graph to random walks.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In addition to the electrical network connection described above, there are important connections to isoperimetric inequalities, see more here, functional inequalities such as Sobolev and Poincaré inequalities and properties of solutions of Laplace's equation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A significant portion of this research was focused on Cayley graphs of finitely generated groups.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In many cases these discrete results carry over to, or are derived from manifolds and Lie groups.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In the context of random graphs, particularly that of the Erdős–Rényi model, analytical results to some properties of random walkers have been obtained.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] A good reference for random walk on graphs is the online book by Aldous and Fill.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] If the transition kernel $p(x,y)$ is itself random (based on an environment $\omega$ ) then the random walk is called a "random walk in random environment".
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] When the law of the random walk includes the randomness of $\omega$ , the law is called the annealed law; on the other hand, if $\omega$ is seen as fixed, the law is called a quenched law.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] See the book of Hughes, the book of Revesz, or the lecture notes of Zeitouni.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] We can think about choosing every possible edge with the same probability as maximizing uncertainty (entropy) locally.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] We could also do it globally – in maximal entropy random walk (MERW) we want all paths to be equally probable, or in other words: for every two vertexes, each path of given length is equally probable.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This random walk has much stronger localization properties.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] There are a number of interesting models of random paths in which each step depends on the past in a complicated manner.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] All are more complex for solving analytically than the usual random walk; still, the behavior of any model of a random walker is obtainable using computers.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] The self-avoiding walk of length *n* on $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ is the random *n*-step path which starts at the origin, makes transitions only between adjacent sites in $\mathbb {Z} ^{d}$ , never revisit a site, and is chosen uniformly among all such paths.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] In two dimensions, due to self-trapping, a typical self-avoiding walk is very short, while in higher dimension it grows beyond all bounds.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] This model has often been used in polymer physics (since the 1960s).
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Random walk chosen to maximize entropy rate, has much stronger localization properties.
[src:metropolis-hastings/random-walk] Random walks where the direction of movement at one time is correlated with the direction of movement at the next time.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] In numerical analysis and computational statistics, **rejection sampling** is a basic technique used to generate observations from a distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] It is also commonly called the **acceptance-rejection method** or "accept-reject algorithm" and is a type of exact simulation method.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The method works for any distribution in $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ with a density.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling is based on the observation that to sample a random variable in one dimension, one can perform a uniformly random sampling of the two-dimensional Cartesian graph, and keep the samples in the region under the graph of its density function.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Note that this property can be extended to *N*-dimension functions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Sample $U\sim \mathrm {Unif} (0,1)$ , independently of X .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] If $W<M\times U$ , reject X and repeat from step 1.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The algorithm will take an average of ${\frac {M}{\int f_{\varpropto }(y)dy}}$ rejections to obtain a sample.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] To visualize the motivation behind rejection sampling, imagine graphing the probability density function (PDF) of a random variable onto a large rectangular board and throwing darts at it.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Assume that the darts are uniformly distributed around the board.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Now remove all of the darts that are outside the area under the curve.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The remaining darts will be distributed uniformly within the area under the curve, and the x ‑positions of these darts will be distributed according to the random variable's density.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] This is because there is the most room for the darts to land where the curve is highest and thus the probability density is greatest.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The visualization just described is equivalent to a particular form of rejection sampling where the "proposal distribution" is uniform.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The general form of rejection sampling assumes that the board is not necessarily rectangular but is shaped according to the density of some proposal distribution (not necessarily normalized to 1 ) that we know how to sample from (for example, using inversion sampling).
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Its shape must be at least as high at every point as the distribution we want to sample from, so that the former completely encloses the latter.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Otherwise, there would be parts of the curved area we want to sample from that could never be reached.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Draw a vertical line at this x ‑position, up to the y-value of the probability density function of the proposal distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] If the sampled value is greater than the value of the desired distribution at this vertical line, reject the x ‑value and return to step 1; else the x ‑value is a sample from the desired distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] This algorithm can be used to sample from the area under any curve, regardless of whether the function integrates to 1.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] In fact, scaling a function by a constant has no effect on the sampled x ‑positions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Thus, the algorithm can be used to sample from a distribution whose normalizing constant is unknown, which is common in computational statistics.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] In the following analysis we assume for simplicity that $f\equiv f_{\varpropto }$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The rejection sampling method generates sampling values from a target distribution with probability density function $f(x)$ by using a proposal distribution with probability density $g(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The idea is that one can generate a sample value from f by instead sampling from g and accepting the sample from f with probability $f(x)/(Mg(x))$ , repeating the draws from g until a value is accepted.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] M here is a constant, finite bound on the likelihood ratio $f(x)/g(x)$ , satisfying $M<\infty$ over the support of f ; in other words, M must satisfy $f(x)\leq Mg(x)$ for all values of x .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Note that this requires that the support of g must include the support of f —in other words, $g(x)>0$ whenever $f(x)>0$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The validation of this method is the envelope principle: when simulating the pair ${\textstyle (x,v=u\cdot Mg(x))}$ , one produces a uniform simulation over the subgraph of ${\textstyle Mg(x)}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] This means that, with enough replicates, the algorithm generates a sample from the desired distribution $f(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] There are a number of extensions to this algorithm, such as the Metropolis algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] This method relates to the general field of Monte Carlo techniques, including Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms that also use a proxy distribution to achieve simulation from the target distribution $f(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] It forms the basis for algorithms such as the Metropolis algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The number of samples required from g to obtain an accepted value thus follows a geometric distribution with probability $1/M$ , which has mean M .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Intuitively, M is the expected number of the iterations that are needed, as a measure of the computational complexity of the algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] When M is chosen closer to one, the unconditional acceptance probability is higher the less that ratio varies, since M is the upper bound for the likelihood ratio ${\textstyle f(x)/g(x)}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] In practice, a value of M closer to 1 is preferred as it implies fewer rejected samples, on average, and thus fewer iterations of the algorithm.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] In this sense, one prefers to have M as small as possible (while still satisfying $f(x)\leq Mg(x)$ , which suggests that $g(x)$ should generally resemble $f(x)$ in some way.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Note, however, that M cannot be equal to 1: such would imply that $f(x)=g(x)$ , i.e. that the target and proposal distributions are actually the same distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling is most often used in cases where the form of $f(x)$ makes sampling difficult.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] A single iteration of the rejection algorithm requires sampling from the proposal distribution, drawing from a uniform distribution, and evaluating the $f(x)/(Mg(x))$ expression.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling is thus more efficient than some other method whenever M times the cost of these operations—which is the expected cost of obtaining a sample with rejection sampling—is lower than the cost of obtaining a sample using the other method.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling can be far more efficient compared with the naive methods in some situations.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The problem is this sampling can be difficult and inefficient, if ${\textstyle \mathbb {P} (X\in A)\approx 0}$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The expected number of iterations would be ${\frac {1}{\mathbb {P} (X\in A)}}$ , which could be close to infinity.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Moreover, even when you apply the Rejection sampling method, it is always hard to optimize the bound M for the likelihood ratio.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] More often than not, M is large and the rejection rate is high, the algorithm can be very inefficient.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The Natural Exponential Family (if it exists), also known as exponential tilting, provides a class of proposal distributions that can lower the computation complexity, the value of M and speed up the computations (see examples: working with Natural Exponential Families).
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Given a random variable $X\sim F(\cdot )$ , $F(x)=\mathbb {P} (X\leq x)$ is the target distribution.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Assume for simplicity, the density function can be explicitly written as $f(x)$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] where $\psi (\theta )=\log \left(\mathbb {E} \exp(\theta X)\right)$ and ${\displaystyle \Theta =\{\theta$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Clearly, $\{F_{\theta }(\cdot )\}_{\theta \in \Theta }$ , is from a natural exponential family.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] It is easy to derive the cumulant-generation function of the proposal and therefore the proposal's cumulants.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The goal is to sample $X|X\in \left[b,\infty \right]$ , where $b>\mu$ .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] holds, accept the value of X ; if not, continue sampling new ${\textstyle X\sim _{i.i.d.}\mathrm {N} (\mu +\theta ^{*}\sigma ^{2},\sigma ^{2})}$ and new ${\textstyle U\sim \mathrm {Unif} (0,1)}$ until acceptance.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] In general, exponential tilting a parametric class of proposal distribution, solves the optimization problems conveniently, with its useful properties that directly characterize the distribution of the proposal.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] For this type of problem, to simulate X conditionally on $X\in A$ , among the class of simple distributions, the trick is to use natural exponential family, which helps to gain some control over the complexity and considerably speed up the computation.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Indeed, there are deep mathematical reasons for using natural exponential family.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling requires knowing the target distribution (specifically, ability to evaluate target PDF at any point).
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Rejection sampling can lead to a lot of unwanted samples being taken if the function being sampled is highly concentrated in a certain region, for example a function that has a spike at some location.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] For many distributions, this problem can be solved using an adaptive extension (see adaptive rejection sampling), or with an appropriate change of variables with the method of the ratio of uniforms.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] In addition, as the dimensions of the problem get larger, the ratio of the embedded volume to the "corners" of the embedding volume tends towards zero, thus a lot of rejections can take place before a useful sample is generated, thus making the algorithm inefficient and impractical.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] In high dimensions, it is necessary to use a different approach, typically a Markov chain Monte Carlo method such as Metropolis sampling or Gibbs sampling.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] If $W_{1}+\cdots +W_{t}<M$ , reject X and repeat from step 1.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] It can be shown that, as $M\rightarrow \infty$ , the output variable of the algorithm $X=X_{M}$ converges in distribution to the desired target with density f .
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Another approach that requires no knowledge of the optimal bounding constant $\sup _{x}{\frac {f_{\varpropto }(x)}{g(x)}}$ is the *empirical supremum rejection sampling* method.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] For many distributions, finding a proposal distribution that includes the given distribution without a lot of wasted space is difficult.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Instead of a single uniform envelope density function, use a piecewise linear density function as your envelope instead.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] We can take even further advantage of the (log) concavity requirement, to potentially avoid the cost of evaluating $f\left(x\right)$ when your sample *is* accepted.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The method essentially involves successively determining an envelope of straight-line segments that approximates the logarithm better and better while still remaining above the curve, starting with a fixed number of segments (possibly just a single tangent line).
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Sampling from a truncated exponential random variable is straightforward.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Just take the log of a uniform random variable (with appropriate interval and corresponding truncation).
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Unfortunately, ARS can only be applied for sampling from log-concave target densities.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] For this reason, several extensions of ARS have been proposed in literature for tackling non-log-concave target distributions.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] Furthermore, different combinations of ARS and the Metropolis-Hastings method have been designed in order to obtain a universal sampler that builds a self-tuning proposal densities (i.e., a proposal automatically constructed and adapted to the target).
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] This class of methods are often called as **Adaptive Rejection Metropolis Sampling (ARMS) algorithms**.
[src:metropolis-hastings/rejection-sampling] The resulting adaptive techniques can be always applied but the generated samples are correlated in this case (although the correlation vanishes quickly to zero as the number of iterations grows).
